Yes, and we've got some great guests helping us with this.

00:02:17.780 --> 00:02:18.300
We do.

00:02:18.300 --> 00:02:24.460
We have Carol Willing and Brett Cannon both joining us to get somewhat of an inside perspective

00:02:24.460 --> 00:02:27.780
on this big, somewhat sad announcement.

00:02:27.780 --> 00:02:29.240
And we're going to dig into that.

00:02:29.240 --> 00:02:30.000
Hello, Carol.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:31.020
Welcome to the show.

00:02:31.020 --> 00:02:31.400
Hi.

00:02:31.400 --> 00:02:32.140
How are you doing?

00:02:32.140 --> 00:02:32.800
Great.

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:33.480
Thanks for being here.

00:02:33.480 --> 00:02:33.860
Hi, Brett.

00:02:33.860 --> 00:02:35.020
Hello, everyone.

00:02:35.020 --> 00:02:35.780
Thanks for having me.

00:02:35.780 --> 00:02:36.480
Yeah, absolutely.

00:02:36.480 --> 00:02:37.240
It's great you're here.

00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:39.760
Brian, you want to tell us what the big news is?

00:02:39.760 --> 00:02:42.080
I think I'm just about as clueless as everybody else.

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:43.440
I'm just in shock.

00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:49.660
Last week, we heard an announcement that Guido was stepping down as the BDFL.

00:02:49.660 --> 00:02:51.460
Yeah, that is a big deal.

00:02:51.460 --> 00:02:57.080
So there's been a little bit of debate about exactly what he meant when he said this.

00:02:57.080 --> 00:02:59.600
You know, was it he's just taking a break?

00:02:59.600 --> 00:03:00.680
Is he actually stepping down?

00:03:00.680 --> 00:03:04.080
So let me just read the salient parts of the announcement.

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:08.880
So this was an email sent to the Python mailing list, Python dev mailing list.

00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:11.460
And the title was Transfer of Power.

00:03:12.060 --> 00:03:15.520
And here's Guido's words, bits and pieces taken from his email.

00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:22.320
Now that PEP 572 is done, I don't ever want to have to fight so hard for a PEP and find

00:03:22.320 --> 00:03:24.260
that so many people despise my decisions.

00:03:24.260 --> 00:03:28.200
I'd like to remove myself entirely from the decision process.

00:03:28.200 --> 00:03:32.220
I'll still be here for a while as an ordinary core dev, and I'll still be available to mentor

00:03:32.220 --> 00:03:34.560
people, possibly more available.

00:03:34.560 --> 00:03:39.180
But I'm basically giving myself a permanent vacation from being BDFL.

00:03:39.180 --> 00:03:41.660
And you all will be on your own.

00:03:41.660 --> 00:03:43.700
I'm not going to appoint a successor.

00:03:43.700 --> 00:03:48.820
The decision, he says basically, summarizing that the day to day stuff is going to be fine.

00:03:48.820 --> 00:03:52.540
But the decisions that matter that may be affected are how PEPs are decided and how new

00:03:52.540 --> 00:03:53.800
core devs are inducted.

00:03:53.980 --> 00:03:58.480
And then finally, sort of on the parting thought, said, I'll still be here, but I'm trying to

00:03:58.480 --> 00:04:00.000
let you all figure something out for yourselves.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:01.740
I'm tired and need a very long break.

00:04:01.740 --> 00:04:03.740
So that was the announcement.

00:04:03.740 --> 00:04:04.680
And that's the big news.

00:04:04.680 --> 00:04:05.980
And that's what we're going to talk about today.

00:04:05.980 --> 00:04:11.240
And first, I just want to say thank you to Guido for doing so much for so long, creating

00:04:11.240 --> 00:04:13.560
one of the most popular programming languages in history.

00:04:13.720 --> 00:04:18.640
I have publicly said this, like, I am personally forever indebted to Guido and the team, because

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:20.800
they basically taught me how to program for real.

00:04:20.800 --> 00:04:26.360
Like, I have an official education in all this, but I have always stated that how to actually

00:04:26.360 --> 00:04:29.900
develop in the real world is entirely down to Guido and the team.

00:04:29.900 --> 00:04:30.260
Yeah.

00:04:30.260 --> 00:04:31.040
Yeah, that's awesome.

00:04:31.040 --> 00:04:35.560
And I think, you know, Guido has done so much, not just for the language, but also for the

00:04:35.560 --> 00:04:36.600
community as well.

00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:43.700
And I know I appreciate from the earliest days when he was designing Python, how he was

00:04:43.700 --> 00:04:49.920
made it accessible for learners and for people to actually use the language.

00:04:49.920 --> 00:04:55.460
And, you know, when I'm teaching people, whether it's with Jupyter or high school students, like

00:04:55.460 --> 00:04:59.540
I'm teaching this week, it's just a pleasure to do it in Python.

00:04:59.540 --> 00:05:05.960
And personally, I have a lot to thank him for, but even more so for the greater group of people

00:05:05.960 --> 00:05:06.620
as well.

00:05:06.620 --> 00:05:06.920
Yeah.

00:05:06.920 --> 00:05:12.440
I don't know if he specifically set out to set the tone as he did, or if it was, it's just

00:05:12.440 --> 00:05:13.220
Guido being Guido.

00:05:13.220 --> 00:05:18.240
But I think he definitely deserves a lot of credit for setting the tone that this community

00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:24.620
has ended up with as being inclusive and welcoming and just basically what makes this community

00:05:24.620 --> 00:05:25.680
as amazing as it is.

00:05:25.680 --> 00:05:25.980
Yeah.

00:05:25.980 --> 00:05:26.980
And it's not just technical.

00:05:26.980 --> 00:05:31.920
I think one of the special things about Python, unlike many languages, is they're sort of professional

00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:34.180
programming languages that can build high-end stuff.

00:05:34.420 --> 00:05:38.600
And there's learning languages that are super basic, but you got to stop to go build real apps

00:05:38.600 --> 00:05:40.000
with something else later.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.000
And this is one of the few languages that you can start simple and finish big with.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:46.740
And so that is really, I think, part of its magic.

00:05:46.740 --> 00:05:51.080
But also, you know, you go to PyCon and these other conferences, and you look around, and the

00:05:51.080 --> 00:05:57.300
people around you look like more like general society and less like a bunch of white guys.

00:05:57.880 --> 00:05:58.660
You know what I mean?

00:05:58.660 --> 00:06:01.900
And to me, that is a really special thing.

00:06:01.900 --> 00:06:02.680
It really is.

00:06:02.680 --> 00:06:07.080
It's not as far as it should be, but it is on the path to where it's on a good path.

00:06:07.080 --> 00:06:09.240
It's unlike other communities that I've been involved in.

00:06:09.240 --> 00:06:10.980
So I think that's also really important.

00:06:11.160 --> 00:06:16.440
When I think Kim as a person, I think he has, his personality has so much to do with it.

00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:23.520
You mentioned PyCon, and one of the things that Ito did at PyCon was I had asked him if he would

00:06:23.520 --> 00:06:30.800
meet a young man called Joshua Lowe, who does EduBlocks, which is this really cool user interface

00:06:30.800 --> 00:06:35.420
that lets you go from scratch to Python code.

00:06:35.840 --> 00:06:40.020
And we were talking about how Joshua had made it over dinner.

00:06:40.020 --> 00:06:47.080
And then the next day, Guido probably spent an hour just hacking with him and made this

00:06:47.080 --> 00:06:52.600
young man's PyCon experience more amazing than it was just the day before.

00:06:52.600 --> 00:06:53.840
That's really awesome.

00:06:53.840 --> 00:06:54.240
Yeah.

00:06:54.240 --> 00:06:57.180
And Brian, you got to have lunch with him at the last PyCon, right?

00:06:57.180 --> 00:06:57.960
That was really fun.

00:06:57.960 --> 00:07:03.200
They did a drawing of people that donated to the Python Software Foundation.

00:07:03.780 --> 00:07:09.200
They drew a handful of names, and I think there were like six or seven of us have lunch with

00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:09.360
him.

00:07:09.360 --> 00:07:15.300
And one of the things that was really interesting at that lunch was we were in around the table

00:07:15.300 --> 00:07:20.920
and talked about what everybody does and what their contribution or not to Python was.

00:07:20.920 --> 00:07:23.560
And it talked about some of the things I was doing.

00:07:23.560 --> 00:07:31.980
I mentioned I have a full-time job, but I also work on trying to teach testing and pytest and

00:07:31.980 --> 00:07:33.720
other development processes to people.

00:07:33.720 --> 00:07:39.520
And he looked at me and said, so you have got a full-time day job.

00:07:39.520 --> 00:07:44.720
How do you have enough energy to deal with all the negative feedback you get from contributing

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:45.240
to Python?

00:07:45.240 --> 00:07:49.280
And I haven't really got that negative feedback.

00:07:49.280 --> 00:07:52.220
And I guess that was a bizarre...

00:07:52.220 --> 00:07:56.260
I thought of it as a bizarre question, but now in context, it makes a lot of sense.

00:07:56.380 --> 00:07:59.000
He was at the center of the pressure points, right?

00:07:59.000 --> 00:07:59.980
That's tough.

00:07:59.980 --> 00:08:04.520
So let's maybe talk about what some of the root causes for this.

00:08:04.520 --> 00:08:10.900
Like, he specifically calls out Pep 572 in his letter that he sent out.

00:08:10.900 --> 00:08:13.540
But I feel like there must be more to that.

00:08:13.540 --> 00:08:18.460
Like, Pep 572 was the straw, not everything.

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:20.780
But Carol and Brett, you guys are more on the inside.

00:08:20.780 --> 00:08:22.640
You probably have more exposure to this.

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:23.720
What do you think?

00:08:23.720 --> 00:08:26.860
Honestly, it was the last straw.

00:08:26.860 --> 00:08:32.340
I don't know what Carol thinks, but I personally figured Guido was probably going to retire in

00:08:32.340 --> 00:08:36.060
the next, I don't know, two, maybe three years.

00:08:36.580 --> 00:08:39.440
Just because he's joked so long about retirement.

00:08:39.440 --> 00:08:43.420
And I think he was just getting ready to just not do it.

00:08:43.420 --> 00:08:48.260
And he's been working on making the projects self-sustaining for quite some time.

00:08:48.260 --> 00:08:53.720
But admittedly, from my perspective, Pep 572 got really nasty.

00:08:53.720 --> 00:09:00.780
It was so much negativity that I think he just got fed up and said, like, look, I've been doing

00:09:00.780 --> 00:09:01.640
this for 28 years.

00:09:01.640 --> 00:09:04.080
I've been putting up with general negativity as well.

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:09.380
And this groundswell was just too much to bear and just like, forget it.

00:09:09.380 --> 00:09:11.080
I don't want to put up with this anymore.

00:09:11.080 --> 00:09:13.900
I'm going to, as he said, he's going to retire.

00:09:13.900 --> 00:09:15.060
He's still the BDFL.

00:09:15.060 --> 00:09:16.360
That for a life bit is true.

00:09:16.360 --> 00:09:22.020
But he's basically said, my last dictatorial declaration is I am not going to make any more

00:09:22.020 --> 00:09:24.360
dictatorial declarations ever again.

00:09:24.360 --> 00:09:25.720
Have fun.

00:09:25.720 --> 00:09:26.600
Yeah.

00:09:26.600 --> 00:09:27.240
Yeah.

00:09:27.240 --> 00:09:28.820
But no, it got extremely negative.

00:09:29.140 --> 00:09:33.400
Like when Guido announced the acceptance of the Pep, the very first tweet at him was

00:09:33.400 --> 00:09:34.060
too bad.

00:09:34.060 --> 00:09:35.000
It's a waste of time.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:40.040
And that was just a very common occurrence of just nothing but negativity.

00:09:40.040 --> 00:09:42.500
There wasn't constructive feedback or anything.

00:09:42.500 --> 00:09:44.280
And it dragged on forever.

00:09:44.280 --> 00:09:49.180
There were some missteps in terms of how it was communicated in terms of a technical aspect

00:09:49.180 --> 00:09:52.600
of how it was communicated through the list, like reposting the Pep.

00:09:52.600 --> 00:09:56.600
But people just really just piled it on.

00:09:56.600 --> 00:09:58.460
And it was just unnecessary.

00:09:58.460 --> 00:10:00.040
It was just not constructive.

00:10:00.040 --> 00:10:04.140
And that's, as Brian pointed out, that's why he asked that question.

00:10:04.140 --> 00:10:05.120
How do you handle the negativity?

00:10:05.120 --> 00:10:08.440
Because there can be a lot of negativity anytime you touch this language.

00:10:08.440 --> 00:10:10.020
People love it for a reason.

00:10:10.240 --> 00:10:14.360
And if there's any hints of you changing something that they don't like, some people really overreact.

00:10:14.360 --> 00:10:21.120
And if you saw my keynote at PyCon US, it was entirely on this topic because it can get

00:10:21.120 --> 00:10:27.580
so overwhelming sometimes when people just jump on you and expect on a part of you so widely

00:10:27.580 --> 00:10:28.080
as Python.

00:10:28.080 --> 00:10:32.620
There's not a small number of people who feel the need to share their opinion and unfortunately

00:10:32.620 --> 00:10:34.960
share it in a unconstructive way.

00:10:35.780 --> 00:10:38.480
And I think it just finally made him just go, yeah, you know what?

00:10:38.480 --> 00:10:40.160
I don't need to ever put up with this ever again.

00:10:40.160 --> 00:10:40.720
Forget it.

00:10:40.720 --> 00:10:42.880
And just said, I'm retiring.

00:10:42.880 --> 00:10:47.980
One thought that I had when we were getting ready for this show was, you know, it's kind

00:10:47.980 --> 00:10:49.220
of related to what Brian said as well.

00:10:49.220 --> 00:10:54.260
Like, you know, has a full-time hectic job at Dropbox, right?

00:10:54.260 --> 00:10:56.960
He's already fully committed to working on stuff.

00:10:56.960 --> 00:11:03.700
And then he's trying to bear the, you know, significant portion of the weight of people

00:11:03.700 --> 00:11:08.000
not wanting changes or demanding changes to Python in various ways.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:14.200
And, you know, do you, Carol, think it would have been different if the PSF had made a space

00:11:14.200 --> 00:11:21.200
to sort of employ, you know, to be in that role and not make it, you know, there's the

00:11:21.200 --> 00:11:24.860
stress of the experience and there's the stress of these are my final two hours of the day

00:11:24.860 --> 00:11:25.860
and I'm already exhausted.

00:11:25.860 --> 00:11:27.220
Now I'm getting this.

00:11:27.220 --> 00:11:27.740
You know what I mean?

00:11:27.740 --> 00:11:32.260
I can't speak for Guido, but I mean, I don't know that that would have solved it.

00:11:32.260 --> 00:11:35.880
I mean, I think he has been doing what he wants to be doing.

00:11:35.880 --> 00:11:41.560
And I think if he had said, hey, I want to do this, people would be, you know, very happy

00:11:41.560 --> 00:11:42.740
to accommodate him.

00:11:42.740 --> 00:11:48.840
I think largely what Brett had said, you know, we were talking in the office here at Jupyter

00:11:48.840 --> 00:11:54.680
the other day and we were saying, we can't believe how long he has shepherded

00:11:54.680 --> 00:12:02.240
the language and dealt with, you know, people's comments and fostered, you know, the direction

00:12:02.240 --> 00:12:02.960
of the language.

00:12:02.960 --> 00:12:12.320
And in many ways, any maintainer will feel over time some burnout when there's negativity around

00:12:12.320 --> 00:12:13.040
a project.

00:12:13.040 --> 00:12:21.000
And I think it's unfortunate that people choose to make things personal when they don't need

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:28.140
to be personal, that they view things with black and white as opposed to wanting to compromise

00:12:28.140 --> 00:12:29.500
over something.

00:12:29.500 --> 00:12:35.200
And I remember when I was facing some burnout and he was one of the people that said to me,

00:12:35.600 --> 00:12:41.680
well, do the things that you really enjoy, electronics and teaching and is really helpful

00:12:41.680 --> 00:12:42.260
advice.

00:12:42.260 --> 00:12:45.280
So I think maybe he's taking some of his own advice.

00:12:45.280 --> 00:12:45.580
Yeah.

00:12:45.580 --> 00:12:48.380
It has been a really long time that he's been working on this.

00:12:48.380 --> 00:12:53.040
I've never worked on a single project for 30 years, right?

00:12:53.040 --> 00:12:55.280
I've not been programming for 30 years, honestly.

00:12:55.960 --> 00:12:59.440
But it just seems like, you know, it's pretty natural for him to step down.

00:12:59.440 --> 00:13:03.460
One thing I really wish, and I, Brian, I think we spoke about this last time.

00:13:03.460 --> 00:13:09.340
I wish he would have just sort of gone into a more, just, I'm kind of stepping back for a

00:13:09.340 --> 00:13:14.940
while and hung in there until after 2020 and Python 3 becomes the one and only Python.

00:13:15.480 --> 00:13:19.920
And sort of that could have been like a celebratory stepping down rather than a, I'm frustrated

00:13:19.920 --> 00:13:21.740
and I'm giving you guys the reins.

00:13:21.740 --> 00:13:26.980
I would have liked to see him retire in some sort of celebration, mission accomplished type

00:13:26.980 --> 00:13:28.060
of experience, you know?

00:13:28.060 --> 00:13:33.760
It would have been nice, but the problem is, is there still the chance of another, I don't

00:13:33.760 --> 00:13:37.740
think uprising is quite the right word, but an explosion of negativity between now and then.

00:13:37.740 --> 00:13:44.020
And while I would like to assume the community has switched over to three and every number I've

00:13:44.020 --> 00:13:45.180
seen has said that.

00:13:45.180 --> 00:13:51.600
I also don't know if the people who are holding onto Python 2 are going to react reasonably

00:13:51.600 --> 00:13:53.820
come January 1st, 2020 as well.

00:13:53.820 --> 00:13:55.960
So I could also see him going like, you know what?

00:13:55.960 --> 00:13:59.920
I don't want to risk having to put myself through that after what he's just gone through.

00:13:59.920 --> 00:14:00.880
Yeah, that's possible.

00:14:00.880 --> 00:14:06.440
I totally get the perspective of it would have been an amazing party January 1st or at PyCon

00:14:06.440 --> 00:14:09.840
in 2020 going like, yeah, we've moved on to Python 3.

00:14:09.840 --> 00:14:13.560
Guido's getting the well-deserved retirement he wants and it would have been an amazing party.

00:14:13.560 --> 00:14:16.980
But instead, we're just going to have just the amazing party for Python 3.

00:14:16.980 --> 00:14:18.680
And I'm personally fine with that.

00:14:18.680 --> 00:14:19.500
We can invite Guido.

00:14:19.500 --> 00:14:21.420
I'm sure he'll be there.

00:14:21.420 --> 00:14:23.120
I don't think that that.

00:14:23.120 --> 00:14:26.440
I mean, he's still the president of the PSF.

00:14:26.440 --> 00:14:29.800
So he obviously is still going to be involved.

00:14:30.040 --> 00:14:33.040
And, you know, it's up to us as the community.

00:14:33.040 --> 00:14:38.500
Much like the SciPy community did last week, they did a really nice thank you, Guido.

00:14:38.500 --> 00:14:47.380
Like they got everybody from the conference together and gave them a very thoughtful thank you, which I've never seen them do for anything before.

00:14:47.380 --> 00:14:49.000
So it was really cool.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:55.620
And I think he has touched so many people in so many different ways that that celebration will come.

