00:16:40.220 --> 00:16:43.240
All right, so you spoke about governance and decision-making and stuff.

00:16:43.240 --> 00:16:48.760
What do you think is going to replace Guido being the final decider?

00:16:48.980 --> 00:16:51.200
It's actually still being actively discussed.

00:16:51.200 --> 00:16:56.460
As the email Guido sent said, he's basically leaving it up to us.

00:16:56.460 --> 00:17:01.780
He did not dictate how we were going to govern ourselves afterwards.

00:17:01.780 --> 00:17:03.440
So he has left it up to us.

00:17:03.440 --> 00:17:08.820
He actually didn't even dictate how we would even choose how we would choose to govern ourselves.

00:17:08.820 --> 00:17:13.940
So there's not even a specific choice yet of how we would potentially vote for this.

00:17:13.940 --> 00:17:16.320
Like some people have said PSF fellows.

00:17:16.320 --> 00:17:18.240
Some have said core devs.

00:17:18.620 --> 00:17:22.180
So there's, it's a completely open-ended question, honestly.

00:17:22.180 --> 00:17:32.140
The current thinking seems to be around, and Carol can obviously correct me if my feeling doesn't jive with hers at all.

00:17:32.580 --> 00:17:39.100
Either potentially another BDFL or a somehow council of elders or some such.

00:17:39.100 --> 00:17:44.800
It seems to be the key thing is just trying to figure out how we want to steward the design of the language.

00:17:44.800 --> 00:17:49.600
We've been managing ourselves daily for quite some time.

00:17:49.600 --> 00:17:52.500
Guido's not directly involved with releases, so that's not even an issue.

00:17:52.500 --> 00:17:57.380
It really comes down to how do we have someone make the final decision on PEPs?

00:17:57.380 --> 00:17:58.580
Who says yay or nay?

00:17:58.580 --> 00:18:00.000
Who makes the technical decisions?

00:18:00.140 --> 00:18:02.760
Who chooses the paint color for the bike shed?

00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:03.860
That kind of thing.

00:18:03.860 --> 00:18:07.320
That's the really key thing we have to still make a decision on.

00:18:07.320 --> 00:18:23.160
Yeah, and I think Brett kind of put it, you know, I think the emails that I've at least seen on Python committers have been very respectful and, you know, really trying to seek out what is going to happen from here.

00:18:23.160 --> 00:18:26.620
And I think Guido's email mentioned four things.

00:18:26.620 --> 00:18:40.320
Day-to-day decisions on the issue tracker and GitHub, how PEPs are decided, which to me is sort of like the direction of the language and who stewards that, how new core devs are inducted, and the code of conduct.

00:18:40.320 --> 00:18:51.000
And if I look at all four of those, the day-to-day decisions, as Brett had said, you know, releases and things like that, we're in a good spot.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:54.260
And we should probably just be doing what we have been doing.

00:18:54.260 --> 00:19:02.380
How new core devs are inducted, I think that will fall out of whatever decision-making we have for the language.

00:19:02.380 --> 00:19:10.360
I know that we've made some progress over the past couple of years, and I continue to see that we will make progress.

00:19:10.360 --> 00:19:28.340
And the code of conduct, I think we're all recognizing that being professional and civil to each other and talking about issues as opposed to whether somebody's intelligence calls, it's called into question or whatever, is not the right way to do it.

00:19:28.400 --> 00:19:29.660
It's better to be professional.

00:19:29.660 --> 00:19:47.900
And, you know, how PEPs are decided, it seems as if, much like Brett had mentioned, that we're sort of converging on maybe three individuals as like a triumvirate or one and no more than five is sort of how I've read it.

00:19:47.900 --> 00:19:48.260
Okay.

00:19:48.260 --> 00:19:49.680
That makes a lot of sense.

00:19:49.680 --> 00:19:53.100
It seems to me whatever the decision is, it should be odd, not even.

00:19:53.360 --> 00:19:55.500
Actually, that came up already.

00:19:55.500 --> 00:20:02.980
And Tim Peters, for those of you who've been in the language for a long time, might recognize the name, who's gotten active again, partially thanks to PEP 572.

00:20:02.980 --> 00:20:08.080
So at least there's one very nice perk from my perspective from what happened with PEP 572.

00:20:08.400 --> 00:20:16.080
pointed out that the odd number in voting typically is very important when you have an either A or B decision and you have to choose one or the other.

00:20:16.080 --> 00:20:25.260
But if you have a status quo or a change, so more of a yes, no decision, having the tie go to the status quo is not quite so critical.

00:20:25.260 --> 00:20:32.020
So we could theoretically go with a four and really not have too much of an impactful problem in that regard.

00:20:32.260 --> 00:20:34.060
Yeah, I guess it would lead to stronger debates.

00:20:34.060 --> 00:20:37.340
You've got to bring someone over to your side if it's a split decision.

00:20:37.340 --> 00:20:40.860
And if they fail to decide, then it just stays the way it is.

00:20:40.860 --> 00:20:41.420
Right.

00:20:41.420 --> 00:20:42.920
Nothing new is adopted, I guess.

00:20:42.920 --> 00:20:43.520
Yeah, exactly.

00:20:43.520 --> 00:20:47.960
So there is a possibility of actually going with four, for instance.

00:20:47.960 --> 00:20:48.760
Interesting.

00:20:48.760 --> 00:20:50.320
I don't think anyone suggested two.

00:20:50.320 --> 00:20:55.300
It seems to be pretty much one, three, four, five seems to be the running numbers right now.

00:20:55.300 --> 00:20:55.680
Right.

00:20:55.680 --> 00:20:56.220
Yeah.

00:20:56.220 --> 00:20:56.820
Interesting.

00:20:56.820 --> 00:20:57.160
Okay.

00:20:57.160 --> 00:20:58.380
Yeah, that makes a lot of sense.

00:20:58.700 --> 00:21:06.360
So I guess the final thing that we should spend some time on is, is this a problem for the community?

00:21:06.360 --> 00:21:10.780
Is this going to hurt Python's fantastic momentum?

00:21:10.780 --> 00:21:16.780
Is this going to hurt the growth or evolution or sustaining Python?

00:21:16.780 --> 00:21:22.520
Or do you think it's just a little bit of change on how decisions are made and not such a big deal?

00:21:22.520 --> 00:21:24.020
Do you want me to take that first, Brett?

00:21:24.020 --> 00:21:24.400
Yeah.

00:21:24.400 --> 00:21:25.220
Yeah, go ahead.

00:21:25.220 --> 00:21:26.240
You go first, Carol.

00:21:26.240 --> 00:21:31.540
So I think the language will continue to thrive and will continue to grow.

00:21:31.540 --> 00:21:33.300
Will some things be different?

00:21:33.300 --> 00:21:33.760
Yes.

00:21:33.760 --> 00:21:35.880
But Guido's made it very clear.

00:21:35.880 --> 00:21:38.540
He's still going to be accessible on mailing lists.

00:21:38.540 --> 00:21:40.760
He's still the president of the PSF.

00:21:40.760 --> 00:21:49.320
The PSF is largely, with the community's support, doing many of the outreach things and things to grow the community.

00:21:50.280 --> 00:22:03.480
And then the core development side of things, I think what you've seen is sort of a shift in some ways away from strictly the language to also, you know, Python has a very rich ecosystem of libraries.

00:22:03.480 --> 00:22:13.840
So things like Jupyter and scipy and scipy wouldn't have come about if Python, the core language, hadn't been so wonderful to work with.

00:22:14.540 --> 00:22:20.960
And so, yes, there was going to be work to do to figure out how to continue the design of the language.

00:22:20.960 --> 00:22:26.420
But I have every belief and commitment that that will happen.

00:22:26.420 --> 00:22:26.980
I agree.

00:22:27.120 --> 00:22:31.240
I think the way I don't think this is going to change the momentum for the language.

00:22:31.240 --> 00:22:35.600
I don't think, honestly, anyone should really be worried at all.

00:22:35.600 --> 00:22:44.640
There might be a slowdown in terms of new features for Python 3.8, which I know some people actually like the idea of.

00:22:45.260 --> 00:22:52.220
Basically, I view it no more as a temporary pause in language-defining changes.

00:22:52.220 --> 00:23:00.220
And honestly, we've had a language moratorium before back for Python 3.3, I believe, which I should know since I helped write the PEP for that.

00:23:00.220 --> 00:23:10.000
So if anything, you can view it as basically just a moratorium on language changes for a little while until we decide how we want to govern those kinds of changes.

00:23:10.260 --> 00:23:12.820
And then it'll just more or less go back to where it was.

00:23:12.820 --> 00:23:26.840
Now, the pace might be slower than it was if, for instance, we go with a council versus another benevolent dictator who could potentially come to decisions faster and just do other things.

00:23:26.840 --> 00:23:30.160
I guess it's potentially more nimbly in my personal view.

00:23:30.160 --> 00:23:38.240
But I really don't see this really affecting the language long-term or even medium-term or basically short-term defending on your definition of short.

00:23:38.240 --> 00:23:40.220
Yeah, for some definition of short, yeah.

00:23:40.220 --> 00:23:43.560
I suspect we'll have this all worked out in the next few months.

00:23:43.560 --> 00:23:50.220
I'd be really surprised if we don't have a solid plan of what our options are by the end of the year and if not already decided by then.

00:23:50.220 --> 00:23:52.140
No, I've got hopefully a quick question.

00:23:52.140 --> 00:24:00.440
I guess I don't know how, when there's discussions on peps, who can participate in those discussions?

00:24:00.440 --> 00:24:02.320
Is it just core developers or?

00:24:02.540 --> 00:24:06.460
I have to caveat this with this was the way it used to be.

00:24:06.460 --> 00:24:08.180
We'll see if this continues.

00:24:08.680 --> 00:24:17.800
But to answer that question, Brian, basically the way we suggest people do peps is they come with an idea to Python ideas, the mailing list, and they propose it.

00:24:17.800 --> 00:24:21.440
And usually pretty quickly, people either go, that's been proposed before.

00:24:21.440 --> 00:24:25.100
No, that doesn't seem very Pythonic.

00:24:25.100 --> 00:24:27.800
Or that seems like a possibly good idea.

00:24:28.520 --> 00:24:37.280
And Guido did on occasion come in and say, yes, there's a possibility for this or would shut an idea down quickly so people didn't waste their time.

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:41.460
And then usually they have a discussion, work out some rough details.

00:24:41.460 --> 00:24:47.500
And then usually the proposer goes away and comes back with a rough PEP saying, all right, here's a more formal proposal.

00:24:47.680 --> 00:24:51.460
And then more discussion on Python ideas to help that author refine it.

00:24:51.460 --> 00:24:55.360
And then what they would do is they would then bring that to Python dev.

00:24:55.360 --> 00:24:57.760
And then with more or less a finalized pep.

00:24:57.760 --> 00:25:01.600
And then any final salient details would be worked out.

00:25:01.600 --> 00:25:14.460
And then either Guido would name what we called a BDFL delegate, who would be someone he delegated the final decision to in terms of technical details and also whether the PEP would be accepted.

00:25:15.360 --> 00:25:19.880
Or he would keep the BDFL vote himself and he would eventually make the call.

00:25:19.880 --> 00:25:36.520
One change that has been floated, though, is to take a PEP from Python ideas to Python dev, you might start needing more of a co-sponsor from a core developer to help make sure that the idea seems solid enough to bring forward and also to make sure the PEP is in a good position.

00:25:36.520 --> 00:25:49.200
Because one of the problems with PEP 572 was while the idea was there, the PEP wasn't fully, fully fleshed out to the level that we typically have peps out from Python ideas on dev as.

00:25:49.680 --> 00:25:57.260
And so there was a lot of repetitious discussion of things that should have been recorded initially in the PEP to have tamped down on the repeated discussion.

00:25:57.260 --> 00:26:04.080
Because the discussion on Python ideas actually was a bit more reasonable than it was on Python dev and less reactionary, funny enough.

00:26:05.080 --> 00:26:10.540
So that's generally the process is idea to Python ideas, then a rough PEP and then refine it.

00:26:10.540 --> 00:26:14.860
And then once it's fairly refined, goes to Python dev, final discussion.

00:26:15.300 --> 00:26:22.300
And then either Guido or a named BFL delegate made a decision and the PEP either got accepted or rejected.

00:26:22.300 --> 00:26:24.600
And that's basically the way it was.

