00:27:24.920 --> 00:27:31.340
Is there a point in that process where the rest of the community can, I guess, add to the opinion?

00:27:31.340 --> 00:27:34.640
So yes, Python Ideas is a completely open mailing list.

00:27:34.640 --> 00:27:37.140
Python Dev is also a completely open mailing list.

00:27:37.140 --> 00:27:40.680
So none of these discussions are happening behind closed doors at all.

00:27:40.680 --> 00:27:46.420
The only mailing list, honestly, that is in any way closed in any of this process is Python committers.

00:27:46.540 --> 00:27:52.240
And that is more technical details that only affect Python core developers themselves and not PEPs.

00:27:52.240 --> 00:27:57.740
So none of these discussions happen in such a fashion that outsiders, outsiders is a bad term.

00:27:57.740 --> 00:28:03.280
People who happen not to be core developers are always able to bring forward their opinion.

00:28:03.740 --> 00:28:17.120
The part of the trick, though, is not having people suddenly pop in and leave their opinion without checking what other people have said or coming in and not understanding how to be professional about leaving their opinion.

00:28:17.980 --> 00:28:26.580
So there's always a balancing act of trying to ask too widely of people who don't quite understand the norms of how to communicate well, honestly.

00:28:26.580 --> 00:28:30.120
But none of the conversation is closed off such that people can't participate.

00:28:30.120 --> 00:28:41.240
So, for instance, Brian, if we had a testing-oriented one, you're totally happy to come in and participate, whether it's at the nebulous stage on Python Ideas or drafting up that PEP or on Python Dev,

00:28:41.240 --> 00:28:47.900
where it's very much more finalized, like very honing into the technical details of how this would work and really thinking through the ramifications.

00:28:47.900 --> 00:28:51.940
And really focus, focus discussion before our final decision is made.

00:28:51.940 --> 00:28:54.140
But as I said, this is how it was.

00:28:54.140 --> 00:28:55.480
I don't know how we're going to tweak it.

00:28:55.480 --> 00:28:56.540
Yeah, that makes a lot of sense.

00:28:56.540 --> 00:28:58.900
Yeah, and it should more or less be the same going forward.

00:28:58.900 --> 00:29:07.400
It just might, we might start being a bit stricter about when PEPs move from Python Ideas to Python Dev to try to make sure the discussion doesn't get rehashed.

00:29:07.400 --> 00:29:12.740
And as Carol pointed out, this has kind of brought forward some code of conduct issues that will probably,

00:29:13.140 --> 00:29:22.940
I know I'm personally working towards refining and have been since PyCon to help try to push even harder to keep the discussion civil.

00:29:22.940 --> 00:29:23.300
Right.

00:29:23.300 --> 00:29:29.580
And I think in addition to just the civility of the discussions, one of the things that I want to look at is,

00:29:30.100 --> 00:29:41.240
can we use some of the great stuff that we have in natural language processing and pull out like the most meaningful content when it comes to comments?

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:51.560
And, you know, part of the issue with 572, there were so many comments that you have to kind of read them all if you wanted like the full spectrum.

00:29:51.560 --> 00:29:55.180
And not all of us have time to do that.

00:29:55.180 --> 00:30:01.840
And so, you know, a way to condense or shorten the period of comments or something.

00:30:01.840 --> 00:30:08.540
And that's as much a social issue and in some ways a conduct issue as it is a technical issue.

00:30:08.540 --> 00:30:13.120
Yeah, that'd be something like in my own community, for instance, in like physical communities,

00:30:13.120 --> 00:30:19.600
everybody is welcome to attend the open city council meetings, but hardly anybody does.

00:30:19.600 --> 00:30:24.680
However, when there's a change that affects everybody, that's usually posted somewhere.

00:30:24.680 --> 00:30:29.180
And then there's like a period of open for community comment or something.

00:30:29.180 --> 00:30:41.880
I'm not saying we need to do that with Python, but I agree with this somewhat, maybe a curated or refereed or some Cliff Notes version of the discussion up till now before somebody can jump in.

00:30:41.880 --> 00:30:45.660
Yeah, and that's definitely something that's been talked about.

00:30:45.660 --> 00:30:50.260
All that puts work on the Python community itself also to do that.

00:30:50.260 --> 00:30:51.400
That's work as well.

00:30:51.400 --> 00:31:06.660
Yeah, and actually, historically, the PEP was supposed to capture all of these details, like the rejected idea and open discussion section, open idea section of every PEP was meant to act as a running summary of the discussion to help prevent that.

00:31:06.660 --> 00:31:14.520
But for instance, in the case of PEP 572, it was a bit overwhelming on the volume, and it can be hard to do that.

00:31:14.520 --> 00:31:26.340
So as Carol mentioned, there's discussion going on now about how we can potentially help alleviate that load on the PEP author whilst making sure that that kind of thing is taken care of.

00:31:26.340 --> 00:31:29.860
Yeah, it sounds like there's some community stuff to do as well.

00:31:29.860 --> 00:31:35.780
But I have faith that you guys will figure something out in terms of the voting and the decision making.

00:31:36.500 --> 00:31:42.220
And I guess I want to sort of echo Carol's thought when I ask about the momentum.

00:31:42.220 --> 00:31:51.160
So much of Python's momentum is with the ecosystem and the extra libraries and PyPI and all of these things.

00:31:51.160 --> 00:31:58.140
And honestly, if the language didn't change one bit for five years, I still think there would be massive momentum in the community.

00:31:58.140 --> 00:32:00.060
So I don't see a real danger here.

00:32:00.340 --> 00:32:00.840
Not at all.

00:32:00.840 --> 00:32:04.720
And honestly, I think the momentum is due to the community.

00:32:04.720 --> 00:32:09.400
And Guido has helped shepherd it forward and bring it to where it is.

00:32:09.400 --> 00:32:17.580
But I think at this point, the language and the community built around it is honestly bigger than Guido at this point.

00:32:17.580 --> 00:32:27.460
So while we'll all miss Guido immensely and his contribution was very important, I don't think the community should worry because the community itself is going to be what carries this forward.

00:32:27.460 --> 00:32:37.820
Yeah. And I think a lot of the core developers, as well as community members, are going to ask themselves, hopefully before they post messages and things like, what would Guido have said?

00:32:37.820 --> 00:32:39.360
What would Guido think?

00:32:39.360 --> 00:32:47.300
You know, put yourself, write your email messages like you're the BDFL and have to convince people.

00:32:47.620 --> 00:32:54.360
I think there are some people that are very articulate and have great ideas and add a lot to improving it.

00:32:54.360 --> 00:32:58.700
